if (str1.equals(str2)) {
    System.out.println("The strings are equal");
} else {
    System.out.println("The strings are not equal");
}
```

In Java, you can compare strings using the `equals()` method or the `==` operator. The `equals()` method compares the content of the strings, while the `==` operator checks if the two string variables point to the same object in memory. 

It is generally recommended to use the `equals()` method when comparing strings, as it is more readable and clear in its intent. The `==` operator can still be used, but it can be easy to forget to use it, which can lead to bugs in your code.

